source in Russia's failure fully to appreciate the value of the individual in comparison with the objectives of the state. Satter explores the moral and spiritual crisis of Russian society. He shows how it is possible for a government to deny the inherent value of its citizens and for the population to agree, and why so many Russians actually mourn the passing of the Soviet regime that denied them fundamental rights. Through a wide-ranging consideration of attitudes toward the living and the dead, the past and the present, the state and the individual, Satter arrives at a distinctive and important new way of understanding the Russian experience.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aAtrocitiesxHistoryxSoviet Union. 0aAtrocitiesxPublic opinionxSoviet Union. 0aAtrocitieszSoviet UnionxHistory. 0aAtrocitieszSoviet UnionxPublic opinion. 0aCommunismxHistoryxSoviet Union. 0aCommunismxPublic opinionxSoviet Union. 0aCommunismzSoviet UnionxHistory. 0aCommunismzSoviet UnionxPublic opinion. 0aPublic opinionxRussia (Federation). 0aPublic opinionzRussia (Federation) 0aPublic opinionzRussia (Federation). 7aHISTORY / Modern / 20th Century.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYUP eBook-Package 2000-2015z978311066772108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press eBook Package 2000-2013z978311053799440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300178425423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780300178425.jpg  a978-3-11-053799-4  Yale University Press eBook Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-066772-1  YUP eBook-Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles